\begin_layout Standard
In the previous section, the probability
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(E)$
\end_inset

 of each event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is known a priori.
 In reality, although each event is assumed to have a probability, the exact
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(E)$
\end_inset

 may not be known.
 If we want to know its value, we can run 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 independent trials.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 denote whether the event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 occurs in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th trial or not, respectively, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(E)$
\end_inset

 could be approximated to given accuracy
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 by the relative frequency
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{N}\tensor*[_{\mathbb{R}}]{\sum}{_{i=0}^{N-1}}x_{i}$
\end_inset

 with the probability converging to one as 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 goes to infinity, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall\epsilon>0,\lim_{N\rightarrow\infty}\pmeas\left(\left|\pmeas(E)-\frac{1}{N}\sideset{_{\mathbb{R}}}{_{i=0}^{N-1}}\sum x_{i}\right|<\epsilon\right)=1\textrm{ .}
\]

\end_inset

This fact is called the law of large numbers
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bernoulli2006,Kolmogorov1950,Uspensky1937,Shafer1976,544199"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we drop a needle of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 onto a floor made of equally spaced parallel lines a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 apart, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell<h$
\end_inset

.
 It is a known fact that the probability of the needle crossing a line is
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\ell}{\pi h}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Buffon1777,DeMorgan1872,Hall1873,Uspensky1937"

\end_inset

.
 We analyze this situation in the mathematical framework of probability
 spaces paying special attention to the resources needed to estimate the
 probability computationally or experimentally.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To formalize the experiment, we consider an experimental setup consisting
 of a collection of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 identical needles of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 We throw the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 needles one needle at a time, and observe the number 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of needles that cross a line.
 The sample space can be expressed as the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{X,-\}^{N}$
\end_inset

 of sequences of characters of length 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 where each character is either 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to indicate a needle crossing a line or 
\begin_inset Formula $-$
\end_inset

 to indicate a needle not crossing a line.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $N=3$
\end_inset

, the probability of the event that exactly 2 needles cross lines
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\{-XX,X{-}X,XX-\}$
\end_inset

 can be estimated by the relative frequency
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Generally, the probability of the event that exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 needles out of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 total needles cross lines can be estimated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{M}{N}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an actual experiment with 
\begin_inset Formula $500$
\end_inset

 needles and the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\ell}{h}=0.75$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hall1873"

\end_inset

, it was found that 
\begin_inset Formula $236$
\end_inset

 crossed a line so the relative frequency is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.472$
\end_inset

 whereas the idealized mathematical probability is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.4774\ldots$
\end_inset

.
 In a larger experiment with 
\begin_inset Formula $5000$
\end_inset

 needles and the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\ell}{h}=0.8$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Uspensky1937"

\end_inset

, the relative frequency was calculated to be 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5064$
\end_inset

 whereas the idealized mathematical probability is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5092\ldots$
\end_inset

.
 We see that the observed probability approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\ell}{\pi h}$
\end_inset

 but only if 
\emph on
larger and larger resources
\emph default
 are expended.
 These resource considerations suggest that it is possible to replace the
 real interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 with rational numbers up to a certain precision related to the particular
 experiment in question.
 There is clearly a connection between the number of needles and the achievable
 precision: in the hypothetical experiment with 3 needles, it is not sensible
 to retain 100 digits in the expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\ell}{\pi h}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is however another more subtle assumption of unbounded computational
 power in the experiment.
 We are assuming that we can always determine with certainty whether a needle
 is crossing a line.
 But 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lines
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the the floor have thickness, their distance apart is not exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, and the needles' lengths are not all absolutely equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 These perturbations make the events 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fuzzy.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Thus, in an experiment with limited resources, it is not possible to talk
 about the idealized event that exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 needles cross lines as this would require the most expensive needles built
 to the most precise accuracy, laser precision for drawing lines on the
 floor, and the most powerful microscopes to determine if a needle does
 cross a line.
 Instead we might talk about the event that 
\begin_inset Formula $M-\delta$
\end_inset

 needles evidently cross lines and 
\begin_inset Formula $M+\delta'$
\end_inset

 needles plausibly cross lines where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta'$
\end_inset

 are resource-dependent approximations.
 This fuzzy notion of events leads to probabilities being only calculable
 within intervals of confidence reflecting the certainty of events and their
 plausibility.
 This is indeed consistent with published experiments: in an experiment
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $3204$
\end_inset

 needles and the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\ell}{h}=0.6$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeMorgan1872"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $1213$
\end_inset

 needles clearly crossed a line and 
\begin_inset Formula $11$
\end_inset

 needles were close enough to plausibly be considered as crossing the line:
 we would express the probability in this case as the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\frac{1213}{3204},\frac{1224}{3204}\right]$
\end_inset

 expressing that we are certain that the event has probability at least
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1213}{3204}$
\end_inset

 but it is possible that it would have probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1224}{3204}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

