Recall that the relative frequency will approximate the probability of an
 event if the event has a probability.
 What if the event doesn't have infinity precise probability because of
 the experimental limit? In this case, two sequences of independent copies
 of experimental results can have their relative frequencies converge almost
 surely to different limits
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Marinacci1999,Teran2014"

\end_inset

.
 In other words, to get a better approximation of the probability, the quality
 of the experimental equipment cannot be compensated by the number of independen
t trials.
\end_layout

